# YAML

Write clear, valid, reviewable YAML from the first draft — not a monolith blob to clean up later.

## Style & structure

- Prefer `.yaml` or match the project’s existing extension (`.yml` vs `.yaml`); don’t mix both for the same kind of file without reason
- Use 2-space indentation (unless the project standard differs); never tabs
- Quote strings when they can be misread as booleans/numbers/null (`"on"`, `"off"`, `"yes"`, `"no"`, versions like `"1.10"`, bare `*` paths, etc.)
- Prefer block style for nested/structured data; use flow style (`{ }` / `[ ]`) only for short, simple inline values
- Keep related keys together; order for readers (e.g. name/id → high-level config → nested details) consistently within a file type
- Prefer several focused files or clear top-level sections over one huge undifferentiated document when the tool allows it
- Be reasonable: don’t split a 15-line compose service into micro-files

## Docs & comments

Spiritually the same bar as Python/HTML: document purpose, comment intent — never narrate obvious keys.

- Every non-trivial YAML file starts with a short header comment describing what it configures and who consumes it
- Comment non-obvious values, coupling, or “do not change without …” caveats
- Comments only where intent is non-obvious — never restate every key name

```yaml
# compose.yaml — local API + DB for development (volume-mounted app code).

services:
  api:
    # Bind-mount source for fast iteration; image rebuild not required for app edits.
    volumes:
      - ./app:/app
```

## Correctness & safety

- Produce valid YAML: consistent indentation, no tab/space mix, correct list vs map nesting
- Prefer explicit types via quoting or schema when ambiguous; avoid relying on YAML’s implicit typing surprises
- Never commit secrets, tokens, or private keys in YAML — use env vars, `.env` (alongside compose when applicable), or a secret store
- For compose/K8s/CI: prefer `${ENV}` / secret refs over hard-coded credentials
- When editing generated or schema-bound YAML (CRDs, Helm values, Actions), match the expected schema and existing project conventions before inventing new shapes
- Keep duplicates and anchors (`&` / `*`) only when they reduce real repetition — don’t obscure readability with clever alias graphs

## Anti-patterns

```yaml
# ❌ BAD — unquoted ambiguous values, secret inlined, no context
enabled: yes
replicas: 01
password: s3cr3t

# ✅ GOOD — quoted when needed, secret from env, brief intent comment
# Feature gate for the beta API path.
enabled: "yes"
replicas: 1
password: "${DB_PASSWORD}"
```
